			        <a>
			          S<sub>N</sub>2 vs. S<sub>N</sub>1
			        </a>
			      </h4>
			    </div>


			    <div id="collapseThree" class="panel-collapse collapse">
			      <div class="panel-body">
			        <p>
•	The biggest difference between S<sub>N</sub>1 and S<sub>N</sub>2 reactions are found at each reaction's rate-determining step.
•	Picture of SN2 mechanism (use SN2 mechanism subtitle for identification)
•	The S<sub>N</sub>2 mechanism is one step and bimolecular (involves two species), often called a concerted step.  The nucleophile attacks the electrophilic carbon from behind and displaces the leaving group. This mechanisms follows this rate law: rate = k[Nuc][R-LG]. 
•	Steric hindrance also plays a huge role in reaction rates. Lower degrees of substitution contribute to faster reaction rates because many bulky substituents causes atomic crowding. Remember that reactivity order depends on degrees of substitution: methyl > 1° > 2° > 3°.
•	Picture of S<sub>N</sub>1 mechanism (use S<sub>N</sub>1 mechanism title)
•	The S<sub>N</sub>1 reaction is a two-step process but is unimolecular (one species is involved).The leaving group is lost, a carbocation is generated, and then a nucleophile attacks the electrophilic carbocation. Remember that carbocation stability increases by degree of substitution: 3°> 2° > 1° > Methyl. The rate law is represented as rate = k[R-LG].

			        </p>
			      </div>
			    </div>
			  </div>


