			    <div id="collapseFour" class="panel-collapse collapse">
			      <div class="panel-body">
			        <p>
•	The type of solvents used can speed up or decrease the rate of a reaction.
•	Picture of Polar Aprotic Solvents (need caption)
•	Polar aprotic solvents do not promote hydrogen bonding because the do not have a hydrogen that can contribute to hydrogen bonding. Aprotic solvents increase SN2 reaction rates because the lack of protons in the solvent does not hinder the nucleophilic reaction. The nucleophile does not react with the solvent.
•	Picture of Polar protic Solvents (need caption)
•	Polar protic solvents are great for SN1 reactions because they stabilize the displaced leaving group with partial positive charges in the solvent. The solvent also stabilizes the carbocation with partial negative charges. This occurs via solvation: the solvent surrounds each species with their partial charge atoms.
